Although the actual occupant remains unidentified, the Imperial Household Agency designates the site as the tomb of '''{{ill|Yamatohiko-no-Mikoto|ja|倭彦命}}''', a son of Emperor Sujin. According to the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}}'', he died in the 28th year of Emperor Suinin’s reign and was interred at Misano Tsukisaka, where his burial prompted an imperial prohibition on sacrificial burials due to their cruelty.

The exact location of Yamatohiko-no-Mikoto’s tomb became unclear over time. During the Edo period, theories emerged linking the tomb to nearby stone chambers such as {{ill|Oni-no-Manaita|ja|鬼の俎}}. In 1877, the Ministry of Interior Historic Site1 the current site as his mausoleum, and by 1886, the area was purchased and restored by the Imperial Household Agency.

However, skepticism remains regarding the accuracy of this Historic Site.

