'''Masuyama Kofun''' (桝山古墳) is an ancient Kofun located in {{ill|Kashihara|ja|橿原市}}, Toya-cho, {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県}}. The kofun is square-shaped and Historic Site1 as the "Imperial mausoleum of {{ill|Yamatohiko-no-Mikoto|ja|倭彦命}}" by the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁}}. It is the largest square Kofun in Japan.

== Overview ==

The Masuyama Kofun is situated on the northern slopes of Kaibuki Mountain, near the southern edge of the Nara Basin. The mound's name derives from its rectangular type. Currently managed by the Imperial Household Agency, the site is preserved as a Historic Site1 imperial burial site.

Originally, the mound was a simple square type, but a front projection was later added to the northeast side, giving it a keyhole-like appearance. The mound measures approximately 85 meters per side and 15 meters in height, making it the largest square kofun in Japan. The mound is composed of three tiers. Fragments of {{ill|Haniwa|ja|埴輪}} have been found on its surface, but further details remain unclear.

Archaeological studies date the kofun to the early {{ill|5th century|ja|5世紀}}, or possibly between the late 5th and early 6th centuries. While the actual occupant is unknown, the Imperial Household Agency has Historic Site1 the site as the burial place of {{ill|Yamatohiko-no-Mikoto|ja|倭彦命}}, a prince of the {{ill|Emperor Sujin|ja|崇神天皇}}.

To the north lies the {{ill|Toya Misanzai Kofun|ja|鳥屋ミサンザイ古墳}}, Historic Site1 as the tomb of {{ill|Emperor Senka|ja|宣化天皇}}, and to the west is the {{ill|Shinzawa Senchizuka Kofun Group|ja|新沢千塚古墳群}}. Their spatial relationships suggest possible cultural or ritual connections.

== Buried Person ==

Although the actual occupant remains unidentified, the Imperial Household Agency designates the site as the tomb of '''{{ill|Yamatohiko-no-Mikoto|ja|倭彦命}}''', a son of Emperor Sujin. According to the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}}'', he died in the 28th year of Emperor Suinin’s reign and was interred at Misano Tsukisaka, where his burial prompted an imperial prohibition on sacrificial burials due to their cruelty.

The exact location of Yamatohiko-no-Mikoto’s tomb became unclear over time. During the Edo period, theories emerged linking the tomb to nearby stone chambers such as {{ill|Oni-no-Manaita|ja|鬼の俎}}. In 1877, the Ministry of Interior Historic Site1 the current site as his mausoleum, and by 1886, the area was purchased and restored by the Imperial Household Agency.

However, skepticism remains regarding the accuracy of this Historic Site.

